Whether the former of these conditions be only a faltering and abnormal exhibition of that which is seen in its true character only in the genius of intuition, is an interesting question, but it does not affect the assumption, that taste is ca- pable of cultivation and refinement.

In claiming for taste a connection with the ac- tive exercise of intellect, we separate it off sharply from dilettaoztez’sm, and from that desultory state which would enfeeble the mind and lay the subject of taste open to grave moral objections. It is in virtue, therefore, of its strict amenability to the rules which apply to other studies, that we claim for it a distinct disciplinal value.

The refinement of the critical faculty is doubt- less the result of a combination of influences.
